â€œFamiliarization of network environment and using network utilities (ipconfig, netstat, ping, arp, telnet, ftp, finger, tracert)â€

ğŸ§ª Experiment No.: 1
Title:
Familiarization of network environment and using network utilities â€” ipconfig, netstat, ping, arp, telnet, ftp, finger, tracert.

Aim:
To understand and use basic network commands to check and analyze the network environment and connectivity.

Apparatus/Software Required:
Computer system

Windows Operating System

Command Prompt (CMD)

Internet connection

Theory:
Network utilities are tools used to test, configure, and troubleshoot network connections.
Some common utilities are:

Utility	Description
ipconfig	Displays IP address, subnet mask, and gateway of the system.
netstat	Shows current network connections and listening ports.
ping	Checks connectivity between local and remote systems.
arp	Displays IP and MAC address mapping.
telnet	Connects to a remote system using a specific port.
ftp	Transfers files between local and remote computers.
finger	Provides information about users on a network (if supported).
tracert	Traces the route packets take to reach a destination.
Commands and Their Use:
Sr. No.	Command	Purpose / Output
1	ipconfig	Shows IP configuration of the system.
2	ipconfig /all	Displays detailed network information including DNS and MAC.
3	netstat	Displays all active network connections.
4	netstat -a	Shows all connections and listening ports.
5	ping www.google.com	Tests connectivity to Googleâ€™s server.
6	ping 8.8.8.8	Checks connectivity using Googleâ€™s DNS IP.
7	arp -a	Shows IP to MAC address mapping table.
8	telnet www.google.com 80	Connects to Google server via port 80 (HTTP).
9	ftp ftp.dlptest.com	Connects to an FTP server for file transfer.
10	finger username@hostname	Displays information about a remote user (if supported).
11	tracert www.google.com	Displays the route data packets take to reach Google.